# Acorns Case Study

## Overview

Acorns is a relatively new FinTech company that specializes in micro-investing. Micro-investing allows users to save small sums of money that are collected over time and once the collection reaches a certain threshold, that money is used to buy a fraction of an ETF. Acorns' primary target market are new investors who either don't know much about investing and are overwhelmed or initimted by various investment options such as stocks, mutual funds, ETFs, IRAs, Roth-IRAs, etc. and/or do not have the funds to meet the minimual account thresholds required by traditional brokers such as Fidelity and Vanguard.  As such, their target market has been traditionally ignored by large brokerage companies which makes their market potential huge. Acorns' primary target market includes low-income, non-savvy investors in addition to millenials. As of 2019, Acorns had over 4.5 million users.[1][3][5]

Acorns was co-founded by Walter Cruttenden and Jeff Cruttenden in 2012 and re-launched in August 2014 to include mobile services. Acorns is currently managed by Chief Executive Officer (CEO) Noah Kerner.  Mr. Kerner has an extensive enterpreneurship background and holds a bachelors degree in both Psychology and Economics from Cornell University.[1][5]

